I've been shopping here since the day they opened, and it's had its ups and downs as far as management, staff and cleanliness are concerned. Things appear stable at the moment-o.k., but not wonderful. (The store changed hands a couple of years ago.) Groceries are high-priced, but it's close to the Borough Hall subway stop and many people pop in on the way home. The deli and salad bar are pretty good, although again expensive. You can find good prices for produce, but have to be selective. The cakes and pastries are often not fresh  and can be passed by without missing anything. Weekends they do a lot of business with families buying lunch on the way to Brooklyn Bridge Park. I have never known anyone to buy catered meals from them. The choices are limited and really inflexible.

Great hot/cold buffet with many foods to choose from. You can now earn a free lunch - spend $10 or more @ the buffet, buy 9 & get the 10th free, from 11am-3pm. I think there shouldn't be a time restriction, though. I usually spend a minimum of $10 each time I buy fron the buffet, but because of the time restriction I've lost out on @ least 3 punches on my card because I didn't make it to the register before 3pm.
I love the fresh food and the option of salads. I've been visiting here for 5 years . Now I'm into the desserts. They have such a wide variety. And I like their fresh flowers too.

Even when the lines are long, they move quickly as the cashiers, many of whom are exotic, know the PLU codes and get you out fast.  The hot salad bar has a good variety but many dishes are too salty for my taste and health.  The receipts ask for customer comments but though I sent email seven times to the management, I did not get the respect of a reply.  I also sent snail mail to Mr. Costa, a manager, recommending that they adopt the paper bags with handles like Trader Joe's as they are easier to carry, hold more food than the flimsy plastic bags, and would appeal to the educated customer crowd for environmental health. No reply to the postal mail either. The fresh fruit, like that of other marketplaces, is mostly hard and under-ripe: don't expect them always to ripen at home even if you place it in paper bags.  They have coffee beans with grinders but I never at any time saw a customer using them.  The non-packaged bread behind the bread counter is always fresh, replaced daily.  I'm not sure what they do with whatever is left over, but they should donate the bread to charity organizations.  As for comments from others, I find that a disturbingly large contribution is that the store is "a bit pricey."  I say: if it's only "a bit" pricey, why bother calling attention to that?  If it's quite expensive, say so.  There is a 10% price cut every Sunday except on sale items.  The dessert choice is extensive, though unlike the system at nearby Lassen & Hennings, you can't now the date that each cake and pie were baked.
A great place to shop.

This survivor of the Garden of Eden chain offers a wide range of gourmet and fancy foods including a large produce department, a respectable deli counter and a fish and meat department that cuts to order, though its inventory varies widely from day to day. The big draw seems to be the variety of prepared food on offer: salad bar, sandwich bar, hot food bar, soup bar, grab-and-go bar. There's also a tempting array of baked goods and chocolates. Prices are on the high side.

You also sometimes have to watch for things past their due date on the shelves, and some deli people are really great but a couple are not so good. Still, you'll find a lot of good food here overall including some fairly upscale stuff.

Most things here are pretty pricey but the fresh sandwiches are made by the best people and if you look all around the store and come at the right times, there are good deals on some of the items. Baked goods are always delicious. On Wed you get a free can of soda with a sandwich, although you will not be reminded, so many leave without getting it for free.

A "gourmet" grocery store with hot food, a salad bar, baked goods, sushi, and deli sandwiches. A little pricey.  This place is next door to my office, so I eat lunch from here a lot. I usually do a sandwich, but I've eaten a lot of food off the bars. You'd think it would get boring, but they have enough variety and they change things up frequently so I'm always finding something I like.  Chicken salad sandwiches and wraps are probably my favorites, but I always check the bars first because they are adding new stuff all the time.  The baked stuff is hit or miss. We've tried a few cakes for special occasions and have been consistently disappointed- especially considering their high prices. The gourmet cookies are the same way. I suspect that a lot of that stuff might sit around too long.  For general grocery items, I've caught them with both higher and lower prices than my neighborhood Key foods for some things. I've actually found a few things that were cheaper at my dega. Prices are all over the place.  The manager-type guys can be a little short and gruff, but the checkout girls all know me and are the greatest. A lot of days I feel like I'm the only person in there speaking English, though.  Time for lunch. I'll be the guy picking over the roasted Brussels sprouts on the salad bar. Look for me.

Perfect lunch spot. I convinced most of my colleagues to become regulars here. I normally get a salad during my visit. As far as the made-on-the-spot salads, I usually get the curry chicken salad with all of the fixings or the pesto chicken salad with a dash of olive oil. The cold/hot bar has a pretty good selection, especially when they serve shrimp empanadas.  They have also expanded their sushi selection.  The only downside to this market is that frequently during the lunch-hour there is a long line but it goes by quickly. Lastly, the staff are friendly.

They have an asinine rewards program that's supposed to give students a discount. It only applies during certain days/times of day and only if your cashier is in a good mood. Pretty decent otherwise, albeit kind of pricey, but I'd rather they never bothered with the rewards at all. Dangling a discount that you can never get just annoys people.
